# Sorting Techniques — Simple Viva Explanation

## 1. Bubble Sort

### Idea

Compare two adjacent elements and swap them if they are in wrong order.

Largest element moves to the end after every pass like a bubble rising upward.

### Example

```text id="exhhjx"
5 3 1

5 and 3 → swap
3 5 1

5 and 1 → swap
3 1 5
```

### Short Viva Line

“Bubble sort repeatedly compares adjacent elements and swaps them until array becomes sorted.”

---

## 2. Insertion Sort

### Idea

Take one element and place it in correct position in sorted part of array.

Works like arranging playing cards in hand.

### Example

```text id="vawdxi"
5 3 1

Take 3 and insert before 5
3 5 1

Take 1 and insert at beginning
1 3 5
```

### Short Viva Line

“Insertion sort inserts each element into its correct position one by one.”

---

## 3. Selection Sort

### Idea

Find smallest element and place it at correct position.

### Example

```text id="mykqhj"
5 3 1

Smallest = 1
Swap with first element

1 3 5
```

### Short Viva Line

“Selection sort repeatedly selects minimum element and places it at correct position.”

---

## 4. Merge Sort

### Idea

Divide array into smaller parts, sort them, then merge them.

### Example

```text id="amjlwm"
5 3 1 2

Divide:
5 3 | 1 2

Sort:
3 5 | 1 2

Merge:
1 2 3 5
```

### Short Viva Line

“Merge sort uses divide and conquer by dividing array and merging sorted parts.”

---

## 5. Quick Sort

### Idea

Choose a pivot element and place smaller elements on left and larger on right.

### Example

```text id="e4kkz4"
5 3 1 4

Pivot = 4

3 1 | 4 | 5
```

Then sort left side again.

### Short Viva Line

“Quick sort selects a pivot and partitions array into smaller and larger elements.”

---

## 6. Heap Sort

### Idea

Convert array into heap tree and repeatedly remove largest element.

### Example

```text id="7jlwmq"
Largest element moves to end one by one.
```

### Short Viva Line

“Heap sort uses heap data structure to repeatedly extract largest element.”

